1. Law degree (JD or LLM) from an ABA-accredited U.S. institution and admission to the Washington bar, required;
2. At least one year experience providing direct representation in Immigration Court and/or before USCIS to asylum applicants and other immigrants seeking humanitarian relief; law school graduates with clinical legal experience may be considered;
3. Excellent legal research, writing, analytical, and organizational skills;
4. Ability to communicate clearly and effectively, both orally in a courtroom setting and in writing;
5. Deep commitment to immigrant rights and working with humanitarian immigrants;
